# SnapReel 🎬

A private video sharing platform with invite-code authentication, shorts-style feed, and personal file areas.

## Features

- 🔐 Invite code registration (one-time use codes)
- 📤 Video upload (MP4, MOV, WEBM, AVI, MKV — up to 500MB)
- 🎞️ Shorts-style vertical video feed with auto-pause on scroll
- 👤 Personal profile with draft/publish toggle and delete
- 👁️ View counts

-----

## Setup

### 1. Install Python dependencies

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 2. Run the app

```bash
python app.py
```

The app will start at: **http://localhost:5000**

The database (`snapreel.db`) and `uploads/` folder are created automatically on first run.

-----

## Default Invite Codes

These codes are seeded automatically on first launch. Each can only be used once:

|Code   |Code   |Code   |
|-------|-------|-------|
|SNAP001|REEL001|KIDS001|
|SNAP002|REEL002|KIDS002|
|SNAP003|REEL003|       |
|SNAP004|       |       |
|SNAP005|       |       |

-----

## Adding More Invite Codes

Open `snapreel.db` with any SQLite viewer, or run:

```bash
python -c "
import sqlite3
db = sqlite3.connect('snapreel.db')
codes = ['CODE001', 'CODE002', 'CODE003']  # change these
for c in codes:
    db.execute('INSERT INTO invite_codes (code) VALUES (?)', (c,))
db.commit()
print('Codes added!')
"
```

-----

## File Structure

```
snapreel/
├── app.py              # Main Flask app (all routes and logic)
├── requirements.txt    # Python packages needed
├── snapreel.db         # SQLite database (auto-created)
├── uploads/            # Where video files are stored
└── templates/
    ├── base.html       # Shared layout and styles
    ├── login.html      # Login page
    ├── register.html   # Register with invite code
    ├── feed.html       # Shorts-style video feed
    ├── upload.html     # Upload a video
    └── profile.html    # Personal file / profile area
```

-----

## Production Notes (for your dad)

- Change `app.secret_key` in `app.py` to a long random string
- Set `debug=False` in the last line of `app.py`
- Consider using nginx to serve uploaded files directly for better performance
- For HTTPS, use Let’s Encrypt / certbot
